               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18361212-name-290" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18361212-name-290" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18361212-name-290" type="surname" value="BOWLER"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18361212-name-290" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN BOWLER</persName>
                  </hi>. I reside in Fleet-street, and am in the service of Mr. Sharp, the banker. I was walking with James William Moss up ship-yard about half-past eight o'clock on the evening in question, and observed a crowd of persons—I went up and saw John Williams and the prisoner Mary Ann, and another female—I saw the boy take Mr. Moss's handker<lb></lb>chief from him—I took hold of him, and this girl dropped my handkerchief immediately, I am sure of it—I told my friend to take the boy, and I took the girl—the said, "It was not me that took it—it was the other girl that has run away."</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Mary Ann Williams.</hi> There were two girls walking up, and I saw a boy take it, I was going to tell the gentleman, and he took me—he said at the office that I did not take it. <hi rend="italic">Witness.</hi> I am quite positive I saw it drop from her hand—she was not a yard from me—I took it, and took hold of her hand—she said, "Do let me go—it was not me that took his hand<lb></lb>kerchief, it was the other girl"—this was in Ship-yard, that leads out of the Strand into Garey-street.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18361212-name-291" type="witnessName">
